posts.raw_content:
So, after 25 years in business I am closing shop.  Unfortunately I still have to go into the workforce.

I applied for a job last Saturday.  Being 56 years old I know my odds are slim.  Although I am more than qualified.

I get a brief e-mail.  Thank you for applying, we will review all resume's and may get back to you.  Kiss of death, I know.  But I persist.  I let an extra day go by and I send a follow up e-mail.

"I am excitedly awaiting my interview and I can't wait to get started in this position.  I have heard nothing but good things about your company and I think my skills will be an asset to your team.  Thank you for your time and have a great day."

Less than an hour later I get an e-mail.  After reviewing your resume we would like to set up a time to talk to you about the position and learn a little more about you.

Interview is Friday.  $60,000 a year job.  Half office work, half warehouse, shipping, receiving.  Me 38 years of doing just that.   One thing I am extremely good at is selling myself.  The only jobs I ever applied to and didn't get were jobs with the government.  I have only had four jobs my entire life but every one started with me on the bottom floor and ended with me in leadership roles or actually building my own manufacturing facility.   

The nice thing is there is a lot of security in this company.  They have a lot of military and government contracts.

I know $60,000 isn't a ton of money but I live a very simple life.  I have no debt.  House is paid off and once I finish liquidating my company will have a nice nest egg to fall back on.  

This is the first job I applied to in 28+ years.
